        <p>The Ipswich economy achieved a record <strong>$15.08 billion gross regional product</strong> in 2024, representing 4.2% annual growth‚Äîsignificantly higher than Queensland's 2.9% average and outperforming major centres like Gold Coast (1.96%) and Logan (2.6%). This robust economic performance has created <strong>95,532 local jobs</strong>, surpassing the council's 2027 employment target three years ahead of schedule.</p>

        <p>With <strong>13,049 registered businesses</strong> operating across the region, Ipswich's business landscape is dominated by micro and small enterprises in manufacturing, construction, transport, and professional services. Recent job growth has been strongest in construction (+793 jobs), manufacturing (+516 jobs), and transport and warehousing (+504 jobs)‚Äîall sectors requiring significant equipment investment and working capital.</p>

        <p>The region's <strong>manufacturing sector alone generates $2.7 billion in annual exports</strong>, whilst major infrastructure projects including Inland Rail, the $1.5 billion Ripley Town Centre, and $700 million hospital expansion are driving unprecedented demand for business finance across construction, logistics, and support services.</p>

        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 italic">Source: <a href="https://www.ipswich.qld.gov.au/News-Articles-Folder/2025/Ipswich-economy-booms-as-it-bursts-through-15-billion-barrier" class="text-[#f97316] hover:underline" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Ipswich City Council Economic Data</a>, <a href="https://www.incahootsco.com.au/the-ipswich-economic-story-in-2025" class="text-[#f97316] hover:underline" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Ipswich Economic Story 2025</a></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

